Airbnb $ABNB filed a lawsuit against New York City over a new law it called a "de facto ban" against short-term rentals set to go into effect in July - Reuters
-Airbnb is suing New York City over new restrictions on short-term rentals. - The rules are set to go into effect in July. - $ABNB claims the rules amount to a "de facto ban" on short-term rentals.

- Hosts must be the lawful occupants and present during the rental period. - Renting an entire apartment or home for less than 30 days was already illegal. Airbnb filed a lawsuit in the Supreme Court of the State of New York. $ABNB

- City councilman Ben Kallos believes the law will reduce illegal short-term rentals and increase permanent housing stock. - New York City is a significant market for Airbnb. In 2022, Airbnb's net revenue from listings in the city was $85 million. $ABNB #NY
- Over 5,500 short-term rentals with more than 10,000 guests are scheduled to start in July. - Airbnb sent a letter to hosts criticizing the new rules as punitive and burdensome. $ABNB
- The new rules are described as extensive and intrusive by Airbnb. - Hosts are required to comply with complex regulations scattered across various laws and codes $ABNB
